message.content:
We start by extracting and computing the necessary values from the financial statements.

Step 1. Debt to Equity Ratio  
• Total Liabilities = Total Assets – Total Owner’s Equity  
  = 12,566,098.56 – 10,964,263.48  
  = 1,601,835.08  
• Total Owner’s Equity = 10,964,263.48  
• Debt to Equity Ratio = 1,601,835.08 / 10,964,263.48 ≈ 0.1461  
Rounded to two decimals, this gives 0.15.

Step 2. Net Profit Margin  
• Net Profit from the income statement = –2,035,736.52  
• Total Revenue = 6,836,701.10  
• Net Profit Margin = (–2,035,736.52 / 6,836,701.10) × 100% ≈ –29.78%

Step 3. Return on Assets (ROA)  
• Total Assets at period end = 12,566,098.56  
• ROA = (Net Profit / Total Assets) × 100%  
  = (–2,035,736.52 / 12,566,098.56) × 100% ≈ –16.20%

Step 4. Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio  
In many cases, the turnover ratio is computed based on average accounts receivable.  
• Accounts Receivable at the beginning = 0.00  
• Accounts Receivable at the end = 3,098,023.69  
• Average Accounts Receivable = (0.00 + 3,098,023.69) / 2 = 1,549,011.845  
• Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio = Total Revenue / Average Accounts Receivable  
  = 6,836,701.10 / 1,549,011.845 ≈ 4.41

Thus, the final solution is:

{
  "solution": {
    "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.15",
    "Net Profit Margin": "-29.78%",
    "Return on Assets (ROA)": "-16.20%",
    "Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio": "4.41"
  }
}
